Conception d'une voiture autonome¶

La mission qui m'a été confié au sein de Future Vision Transport est de segmenter les images traitées par Franck au préalable. Nous allons entrainer différents modèles et selectionner le plus performant, puis deployer le modèle sur Azure qui sera accessible via API afin de faire de nouvelle prédiction facilement.

path_original_image = 'data/leftImg8bit/'

def lenght_dataset(path):
    count_train = 0
    count_val = 0
    count_test = 0
    
    for directory in os.listdir(path):
        if directory == "train":
            path_train = path + 'train/'
            for subdir in os.listdir(path_train):
                count_train += len(os.listdir(path_train + subdir))
                
        if directory == "val":
            path_val = path + 'val/'
            for subdir in os.listdir(path_val):
                count_val += len(os.listdir(path_val + subdir))
                
        if directory == "test":
            path_test = path + 'test/'
            for subdir in os.listdir(path_test):
                count_test += len(os.listdir(path_test + subdir))
                
    
    print('Train dataset:', count_train, 'images.')
    print('Val dataset:', count_val, 'images.')
    print('Test dataset:', count_test, 'images.')

I) Mise en place des données¶

1.1) Creation des fonctions pour la mise en place des données¶

Nous allons ici mettre en place nos données afin de pouvoir entrainer nos différents modèles. Nous allons aussi mettre en place un moyen de passer des 34 classes aux 8 principales classes.

Differents dictionnaires qui nous serons utiles pour faire la correspondance entre les 34 classes de base et les 8 classes au final :

# name to label object

# id to label object
labelid2catid = {label.id: label[4] for label in labels}

trainId2label = {label.trainId: label for label in reversed(labels)}

# category to list of label objects
category2labels = {}
for label in labels:
    category = label.category
    if category in category2labels:
        category2labels[category].append(label)
    else:
        category2labels[category] = [label]
        
# id to label object
catid2color = {label[0].categoryId: list(label[0].color) for label in category2labels.values()}
category2catid = {cat: label[0].categoryId for cat, label in category2labels.items()}

Creation de notre générateur qui va permettre de faire du multiprocessing :

In [190]:
class Generator(Sequence):
    
    def __init__(self, images_dir_list, masks_dir_list,cat2id,
                 labelid2catid,dim=(256,128), apply_augmentation=False,
                 batch_size=1, shuffle=False):
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.indexes = np.arange(len(images_dir_list))
        self.apply_augmentation = apply_augmentation
        self.images_fps = images_dir_list
        self.masks_fps = masks_dir_list
        self.dim = dim
        self.class_values = [idx for idx in cat2id.values()] # class values on masks
        self.labelid2catid = labelid2catid

        self.on_epoch_end()

    def __getitem__(self, i):

        # Our final batches of images and masks
        images = [] 
        masks = []

        # Get in the list of images by 16 images for each batch
        for n, (image_path, mask_path) in enumerate(zip(self.images_fps[i*self.batch_size:(i+1)*self.batch_size], 
                                                        self.masks_fps[i*self.batch_size:(i+1)*self.batch_size])):
            
            # read image and resize
            image = cv2.imread(str(image_path))
            image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
            image = cv2.resize(image, self.dim)
            
            # read mask and resize
            mask = cv2.imread(str(mask_path), 0)
            mask = cv2.resize(mask, self.dim)

            # Transform 34 classes to 8 classes
            for label_id, cat_id in self.labelid2catid.items():
                    mask[mask==label_id] = cat_id

            # extract 8 classes as depth/channels
            masks_channels = [(mask == v) for v in self.class_values]
            mask = np.stack(masks_channels, axis=-1).astype('float')
            
            # apply data augmentation
            if self.apply_augmentation:
                transform = get_training_augmentation()
                if transform is not None:
                    sample = transform(image=image, mask=mask)
                    image_aug, mask_aug = sample['image'], sample['mask']
                    
                    # append image and mask augmented
                    images.append(image_aug)
                    masks.append(mask_aug)
                
                # append image and mask not augmented
                images.append(image)
                masks.append(mask)
            else:
                # append image and mask not augmented
                images.append(image)
                masks.append(mask)
        
        # return batches of images and masks
        return np.array(images), np.array(masks)

    
    def __len__(self):
        """Denotes the number of batches per epoch"""
        return int(np.ceil(len(self.images_fps) / float(self.batch_size)))

Definissons une fonction pour appliquer de la data augmentation à nos images :

In [191]:
def get_training_augmentation():
    
    # Our 4 functions of augmentation
    train_transform = [
        A.HorizontalFlip(p=1),
        A.RandomBrightnessContrast(p=1),
        A.GaussianBlur(p=1),
        A.Affine(rotate=(-30,30),p=1),
    ]
    
    # get an integer randomly between 0 and 4 (included)
    k = random.randint(0,4)
    
    if k == 0:
        return None # No data augmentation will be apply
    else:
        return A.SomeOf(train_transform, n=k) # Apply k function of augmentation randomly

# helper function for data visualization
def visualize(**images):
    """PLot images in one row."""
    n = len(images)
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 28))
    for i, (name, image) in enumerate(images.items()):
        plt.subplot(6, 3, i + 1)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        plt.title(' '.join(name.split('_')).title())
        plt.imshow(image)
    plt.show()
    
# helper function for data visualization    
def denormalize(x):
    """Scale image to range 0..1 for correct plot"""
    x_max = np.percentile(x, 98)
    x_min = np.percentile(x, 2)    
    x = (x - x_min) / (x_max - x_min)
    x = x.clip(0, 1)
    return x

II) Modélisations¶

Nous allons essayer différentes simulations:

  1. Modèles: Unet et LinkNet
  2. Backbones: VGG19, ResNet18, MobileNet
  3. Loss: Jaccard Loss
    • Cette fonction loss est l'inverse de la métrique IoU et permet d'optimiser son score.
  4. Metriques: IoU (Jaccard)
    • Cette metrique qui est définie comme étant l'intersection de deux ensembles divisés par l'union de ces deux ensembles, permet dans notre cas de comparer le masque d'origine de l'image avec le masque prédit par le modèle. Donc si nos deux ensembles (ici notre masque d'origine et notre masque prédit) peuvent se superposer parfaitement (en termes de pixels) alors l'intersection des deux ensembles est égale à l'union, ayant ainsi un score de 1 de IoU. Dans le cas contraire où les ensembles ne se superpose pas parfaitement alors l'union des deux ensembles sera plus grand et le score IoU diminuera.

2.1) Mise en place des modèles¶

Mise en place de la fonction d'entrainement :

In [10]:
df_results = pd.DataFrame(columns=['model', 'augmentation','image_size','train_time_epoch','loss_score','iou_score'])#'dice_coeff'])

# Function to make a DataFrame of results
def update_results(df_results, dict_results):
    df_results = df_results.append({
        'model': dict_results['name_model'],
        'augmentation': dict_results['augmentation'],
        'image_size': dict_results['image_size'],
        'train_time_epoch': dict_results['train_time_epoch'],
        'loss_score': dict_results['loss_score'],
        'iou_score': dict_results['iou_score'],
    }, ignore_index=True)
    
    df_results.to_csv(f"output/{dict_results['name_model']}_{dict_results['image_size']}_{dict_results['augmentation']}/results.csv",
                     index=False)
    
    return df_results

# Function to train models
def compute(name_model, model, size, train_gen, val_gen, augmentation=False):

    model.compile(loss=sm.losses.JaccardLoss(), optimizer='adam', metrics=[sm.metrics.IOUScore(threshold=0.5)])
    start_time = time()
    hist = model.fit(train_gen, validation_data=val_gen, epochs=EPOCHS,
                     callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1, patience=5),
                                ModelCheckpoint(f"output/{name_model}_{size[0]}_{size[1]}_{augmentation}/model.h5",
                                                monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True),])
                                #Visualize(X_val_path, c_val_path, (size,size))])
    train_time = time() - start_time
    
    # eval model
    results_eval = model.evaluate(val_gen)
    
    
    return {
        'name_model': name_model,
        'model': model,
        'history': hist,
        'augmentation': augmentation,
        'image_size': size,
        'train_time_epoch': train_time/EPOCHS,
        'loss_score': results_eval[0],
        'iou_score': results_eval[1],
    }

# Function to plot history of training
def plot_history(history):
    # Plot training & validation iou_score values
    plt.figure(figsize=(30, 12))
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.plot(history.history['iou_score'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_iou_score'])
    plt.title('Model iou_score')
    plt.ylabel('iou_score')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')

    # Plot training & validation loss values
    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Model loss')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

In [13]:
def compute_all_models(df_results):
    
    models = ['unet', 'linknet']
    backbones = ['vgg19','resnet18','mobilenet']
    aug_bools = [True, False]

    for model in models:
        for backbone in backbones:
            for aug_bool in aug_bools:

                model_name = f'{model}_{backbone}'
                print(model_name)

                train_gen = Generator(X_train_path, y_train_path,
                                          cat2id=category2catid, labelid2catid=labelid2catid,
                                          dim=(256,128), apply_augmentation=aug_bool,
                                          batch_size=BATCH_SIZE, shuffle=False)

                val_gen = Generator(X_val_path, y_val_path,
                                    cat2id=category2catid, labelid2catid=labelid2catid,
                                    dim=(256,128),batch_size=1, shuffle=False)

                if model == 'unet':
                    model_compute = sm.Unet(backbone, classes=8, activation='softmax')
                elif model == 'linknet':
                    model_compute = sm.Linknet(backbone, classes=8, activation='softmax')




                results = compute(model_name, model_compute, (256,128), train_gen, val_gen, augmentation=aug_bool)
                df_results = update_results(df_results, results)

Nous voyons que les modèles entrainés avec de la data augmentation ont de meilleures perfomances que ceux sans data augmentation, sauf pour le cas du modèle Unet + ResNet18.

La meilleure performance est atteinte par Unet + MobileNet avec une taille d'image de 256 pixels par 128 pixels avec data augmentation. Le modèle obtient 0.636 de IoU avec un temps d'entraiement par epoch de 157s qui est proche de la moyenne 152s.

Nous allons donc utiliser ce modèle comme modèle final.

In [100]:
# callback Azure to save logs
class AzureMlKerasCallback(Callback):

    def __init__(self, run):
        super(AzureMlKerasCallback, self).__init__()
        self.run = run

    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):
        logs = logs or {}
        send = {}
        send['epoch'] = epoch
        for k, v in logs.items():
            if isinstance(v, (np.ndarray, np.generic)):
                send[k] = v.item()
            else:
                send[k] = v
        for k, v in send.items():
            if isinstance(v, list):
                self.run.log_list(k, v)
            else:
                self.run.log(k, v)

    # Create an Azure Machine Learning monitor callback
    azureml_cb = AzureMlKerasCallback(run)

    # Training
    model.fit(train_gen, validation_data=val_gen, epochs=EPOCHS,
                     callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1, patience=5),
                                checkpoint_cb,
                                azureml_cb])


    # Load the best model
    model = tf.keras.models.load_model(model_path, custom_objects={'jaccard_loss':sm.losses.JaccardLoss(),
                                                   'iou_score':sm.metrics.IOUScore(threshold=0.5)})

    # Score trained model
    scores = model.evaluate(val_gen)
    print('Test jaccard_loss:', scores[0])
    run.log('Test jaccard_loss', scores[0])
    print('Test iou_score:', scores[1])
    run.log('Test iou_score', scores[1])

    # Upload the best model
    run.upload_file(model_name, model_path)

    # Register the best model
    run.register_model(model_name, model_path=model_name, model_framework="Custom")

3.5) Deploiement¶

Déployons enfin notre modèle enregistré sur Azure pouur y avoir accès via une API que nous pouront utiliser dans une web app :

In [125]:
from azureml.core.environment import Environment
from azureml.core.conda_dependencies import CondaDependencies
from azureml.core.model import InferenceConfig
from azureml.core.webservice import AciWebservice, Webservice

model_name = "model_final.h5"
service_name = 'self-driving-service'
model = Model(ws, model_name)

env = Environment.from_conda_specification(name=service_name, file_path="dependencies.yml")
inference_config = InferenceConfig(entry_script="score.py", environment=env)
deployment_config = AciWebservice.deploy_configuration(cpu_cores=1, memory_gb=2)

service = Model.deploy(ws, service_name, [model], inference_config, deployment_config, overwrite=True)
service.wait_for_deployment(show_output=True)

print(service.state)
print("Scoring URL: " + service.scoring_uri)

Tips: You can try get_logs(): https://aka.ms/debugimage#dockerlog or local deployment: https://aka.ms/debugimage#debug-locally to debug if deployment takes longer than 10 minutes.
